@Sam Lyons

I've never lived abroad so I can't really reliably relate to your experience. Europe is so different from the US though I think I can imagine how weird it must feel to you. I know I would not be able to live in the States - on both of our month-long trips everything there seemed uncannily alien and familiar at the same time. There was an undercurrent of European heritage about most of the culture, but all the details - and much of the major stuff, too - was completely alien. The threateningly unfriendly police, the guns, the ever-present religion, the oversized cars, the rudimentary public infrastructure and services, the smilingly subservient staff at business establishments, the gargantuan portion sizes, the synthetic ingredients of the preternaturally moist and pale gas station sandwiches - it would all be too much for me to take in the long run.

That being said, my wife and I found the landscapes of the US, and of Utah in particular, incredibly beautiful. The grandness of the vistas, the striking colors - wow, just wow. The fake smiles of most servers and shopping assistants notwithstanding, we met countless friendly, wonderful people there, too. The few days we spent in and around Moab were unforgettable. I would love to go back, as a tourist. Maybe after 2029...

